Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Belarus. You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities.
The Belarusian government have not put in place any restrictions on entering the country and Belavia, the national airline, continues to operate as normal to the UK. Your travel may be impacted by the restrictions put in place by neighbouring countries, and the situation in Belarus could quickly change. You should check with your airline or travel company for the latest information before you travel. You should also check FCO travel advice for Russia, Ukraine, Poland, Lithuania, and Latvia. See Health.
You’ll need to have valid medical insurance before travelling to Belarus. You’ll be asked to provide proof of your insurance when you apply for your visa or when you arrive at Minsk airport under the visa-free regime. Contact the Embassy of the Republic of Belarus for full details of what’s required.
Although there is no recent history of terrorism in Belarus, attacks cannot be ruled out. Attacks could happen anywhere and could affect western interests and places visited by foreigners. See Terrorism
Around 14,000 British nationals visit Belarus every year. Most visits are trouble-free.
If you’re abroad and you need emergency help from the UK government, contact the nearest British embassy, consulate or high commission.
Take out comprehensive travel and medical insurance before you travel.
